---
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';

const faqs = [
  { q: 'How do I password protect a PDF for free?', a: 'Use PDFWonder\'s free Protect PDF tool. Upload your PDF, enter a password, and download the encrypted PDF. Encryption is done entirely in your browser with AES-128 — your file and password are never sent to any server.' },
  { q: 'What encryption does the PDF password use?', a: 'PDFWonder uses AES-128 encryption, the same standard used by Adobe Acrobat and professional PDF software. AES-128 is widely accepted as highly secure.' },
  { q: 'Can someone remove the password from my PDF?', a: 'If someone knows the correct password, they can remove it using a PDF tool. Without the password, a properly AES-128-encrypted PDF cannot be practically recovered by brute force for typical password lengths.' },
  { q: 'What is the difference between user password and owner password?', a: 'The user password is required to open the PDF. The owner password controls what the user can do after opening — such as printing, copying text, or editing. Both can be set; the owner password defaults to the user password if not specified separately.' },
  { q: 'How do I remove a password from a PDF?', a: 'Open the password-protected PDF in your browser (Chrome, Edge) which will prompt for the password. After entering it, print to PDF (Ctrl+P → Save as PDF) to get an unprotected copy.' },
  { q: 'Is my PDF password stored by PDFWonder?', a: 'No. Your password is only used inside your browser to encrypt the PDF using pdf-lib. It is never transmitted to any server or stored anywhere. Once you close the tab, it is gone.' },
];
---

<BlogLayout
  title="How to Password Protect a PDF for Free Online (AES-128 Encrypted)"
  description="Learn how to add a password to a PDF file for free using browser-based encryption. Also covers Adobe Acrobat, Word, and Mac Preview methods."
  canonical="/blog/how-to-password-protect-pdf"
  date="2026-06-07"
  readTime="5 min read"
  category="PDF Guide"
  faqs={faqs}
>

<p>
  Protecting a PDF with a password prevents unauthorised people from opening it. Whether you are sending a confidential report, a private contract, or sensitive personal data, adding a password to your PDF is a quick way to add a layer of security. This guide shows you how to do it for free.
</p>

<h2>Method 1: Free Browser-Based PDF Encryptor (No Upload, AES-128)</h2>

<p>
  <a href="/pdfwonder/pdf-password-protect">PDFWonder's Protect PDF tool</a> encrypts your PDF with AES-128 entirely in your browser. Your file and password are never sent to any server.
</p>

<ol>
  <li>Go to the <a href="/pdfwonder/pdf-password-protect">Protect PDF tool</a>.</li>
  <li>Upload your PDF.</li>
  <li>Enter a <strong>user password</strong> (required to open the PDF).</li>
  <li>Optionally enter an <strong>owner password</strong> (controls editing/printing permissions).</li>
  <li>Click <strong>Encrypt &amp; Download</strong>.</li>
  <li>The encrypted PDF is downloaded to your device.</li>
</ol>

<a href="/pdfwonder/pdf-password-protect" class="tool-cta">
  <div class="cta-label">Free Tool</div>
  <div class="cta-title">Protect PDF — Password Encrypt Free →</div>
  <div class="cta-desc">AES-128 encryption entirely in your browser. Your PDF and password never leave your device.</div>
</a>

<h2>Method 2: Password Protect a PDF in Adobe Acrobat</h2>

<p>
  Adobe Acrobat Pro (paid) gives the most control:
</p>
<ol>
  <li>Open your PDF in Adobe Acrobat.</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>File → Properties → Security</strong> tab.</li>
  <li>Change the Security Method to <strong>Password Security</strong>.</li>
  <li>Check <strong>Require a password to open the document</strong>.</li>
  <li>Enter your password, set permissions, and click <strong>OK</strong>.</li>
  <li>Save the PDF.</li>
</ol>
<p>
  Acrobat also lets you restrict copying, printing, and editing separately from the open password, giving granular control.
</p>

<h2>Method 3: Password Protect PDF in Microsoft Word (Before Exporting)</h2>

<p>
  If you are creating the document in Word first, you can add a password during the PDF export:
</p>
<ol>
  <li>Go to <strong>File → Save As → Browse</strong>.</li>
  <li>Change the file type to PDF.</li>
  <li>Click <strong>Options</strong>.</li>
  <li>Check <strong>Encrypt the document with a password</strong>.</li>
  <li>Enter and confirm your password.</li>
  <li>Click OK and Save.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Method 4: Password Protect PDF on Mac</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Open the PDF in <strong>Preview</strong>.</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>File → Export as PDF</strong>.</li>
  <li>Check <strong>Encrypt</strong>.</li>
  <li>Enter and verify the password.</li>
  <li>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Choosing a Strong PDF Password</h2>

<p>
  A strong PDF password should be:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>At least 12 characters long</strong> — longer passwords are exponentially harder to crack</li>
  <li><strong>A mix of uppercase, lowercase, numbers, and symbols</strong> — e.g., "Tr0ub4dor&3" is much stronger than "password123"</li>
  <li><strong>Not a dictionary word or common phrase</strong> — dictionary attacks can crack simple passwords quickly</li>
  <li><strong>Unique</strong> — do not reuse passwords across multiple protected PDFs or accounts</li>
</ul>
<p>
  Store the password securely in a password manager (like Bitwarden or 1Password). If you lose it, the encrypted PDF cannot be recovered.
</p>

<h2>What Permissions Can You Set on a Password-Protected PDF?</h2>

<p>
  Beyond the open password, PDF encryption allows you to control what authenticated users can do:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Printing:</strong> Allow high-resolution printing, low-resolution printing, or no printing</li>
  <li><strong>Copying text:</strong> Allow or block the ability to select and copy text from the PDF</li>
  <li><strong>Editing:</strong> Block users from modifying the content, even after opening</li>
  <li><strong>Form filling:</strong> Allow or restrict filling in interactive form fields</li>
  <li><strong>Annotating:</strong> Allow or restrict adding comments and annotations</li>
</ul>
<p>
  Our browser-based tool applies sensible defaults: printing is allowed at high resolution, but copying and editing are restricted to protect your content.
</p>

<h2>How to Remove a Password From a PDF</h2>

<p>
  If you need to unlock a PDF you own (and you know the password):
</p>
<ol>
  <li>Open the password-protected PDF in Chrome or Edge.</li>
  <li>Enter the password when prompted.</li>
  <li>Press <strong>Ctrl+P</strong> (or Cmd+P on Mac) to open the print dialog.</li>
  <li>Change the printer/destination to <strong>Save as PDF</strong>.</li>
  <li>Click Save — the new PDF will be unprotected.</li>
</ol>

